<HEADLINE>
<P>
REAL ESTATE AND THE LAW; ATTORNEY KNOWINGLY SELLS DEFECTIVE HOME 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By R.J.B., Special to The Times 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Donald and Patricia filed for divorce. When they couldn't agree on how to sell 
their house, the court appointed Joel, an attorney, to act as a receiver to 
sell the house. He listed the house for sale with a realtor at $539,500, then 
reduced the price to $499,500, and then to $469,500. 
</P>
<P>
 Joel accepted an offer of $355,000 from Timothy whose purchase offer was 
contingent upon a satisfactory professional inspection. But the inspector found 
structural defects, including a defective beam, so Timothy canceled his 
purchase. 
</P>
<P>
 Then Victor and Heidi made a $350,000 purchase offer, which Joel accepted, 
contingent upon a professional inspection. However, their inspector didn't 
mention the defective beam and they proceeded with the purchase. However, soon 
after closing the sale and moving into the house several structural defects 
became obvious, including a sagging and progressively collapsing roof. 
</P>
<P>
 The buyers sued Joel for intentional misrepresentation, intentional 
concealment of material facts, negligent misrepresentation and attorney 
malpractice. But he argued he has judicial immunity, the same as a judge, since 
he was appointed by the court to sell the house. 
</P>
<P>
 If you were the judge, would you rule attorney Joel has judicial immunity from 
liability and the lawsuit against him should be dismissed? 
</P>
<P>
 The judge said no. 
</P>
<P>
 There are two possible viewpoints, the judge began. One is to treat attorney 
Joel as a representative of the sellers and the other is to view him as a 
court-appointed administrator with judicial immunity, the judge explained. 
</P>
<P>
 Since Joel was acting like a receiver for the sale of the house, the judge 
continued, he became an alter-ego for the disputing sellers. Joel was paid for 
his services but he failed to inform the buyers of defects in the house of 
which he was aware from the first inspection, the judge emphasized. 
</P>
<P>
 The high standards governing court-appointed receivers in the sale of property 
should be applied to Joel, the judge ruled. Therefore, he does not have 
judicial immunity and is liable if he breached his duty to disclose the house's 
defects to the buyers, the judge concluded. 
</P>
<P>
 Based on the 1993 decision by the Superior Court of New Jersey in Starr vs. 
Reinfeld, 630 A.2d 801. R.J.B. 
</P>
</TEXT>
