<HEADLINE>
<P>
TWO BANKS TO REDRESS RACIAL LOAN REJECTIONS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A bank in Mississippi and another in South Dakota agreed Friday to settle race 
discrimination cases by setting aside nearly $1 million to compensate blacks 
and Native Americans denied loans or overcharged on the basis of race. 
</P>
<P>
 The agreements between the Justice Department and the First National Bank of 
Vicksburg, Miss., and Blackpipe State Bank in Martin, S.D., were announced by 
Atty. Gen. Janet Reno and submitted to federal judges for their approval. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA012394-0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 006490 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
January 23, 1994, Sunday, Bulldog Edition 
</P>
